Azure charges for resources based on consumption — you pay for what you use, when you use it. The main cost dimensions are compute, storage, networking, and managed services. Compute is charged per hour or per second for virtual machines, App Service plans, and A-K-S nodes. Storage is charged per gigabyte stored plus per operation for reads, writes, and lists. Networking charges apply to egress — outbound data leaving Azure to the internet or to another region. Ingress — data entering Azure — is free. Data moving between services within the same region is also generally free. The fundamental rule is: egress costs money, ingress does not.

Azure provides two planning tools before you deploy anything. The Azure Pricing Calculator lets you configure specific services, regions, and usage patterns to estimate your monthly cost. The Azure T-C-O Calculator — Total Cost of Ownership — helps you compare the full cost of running workloads on-premises versus in Azure, accounting for hardware, software licences, data centre facilities, and IT labour. These tools help you build a business case and avoid budget surprises.

Now let us look at Azure Cost Management.

Azure Cost Management is the portal experience for viewing actual spending, analysing trends, and setting controls. The Cost Analysis view lets you visualise your spending broken down by any combination of scope, time period, and grouping dimension. The scope can be a management group, subscription, resource group, or individual resource. Grouping dimensions include resource type, service name, region, resource group, and tag values. You can view an accumulated cost chart showing your spend to date against your budget, a daily cost chart showing your spending rate over time, and a breakdown by service or resource. Custom views can be saved and shared with your team.

Budgets are the primary cost control mechanism. A budget sets a spending threshold and monitors actual or forecasted spend against it. You configure the scope — a subscription or resource group — the reset period, which can be monthly, quarterly, or annually — and one or more alert conditions. A typical setup alerts the team by email when actual spend reaches 80 percent of the budget and again when forecasted spend is projected to reach 110 percent. Budgets can also trigger an Action Group, which in turn can call an Azure Function or Logic App — enabling automated responses such as shutting down development virtual machines when the budget is exhausted.

Azure Cost Management also supports scheduled cost exports. You can configure an automatic export of your cost data to an Azure Storage Account in C-S-V format on a daily or monthly basis. This is commonly used to feed spending data into Power BI for custom dashboards or into internal chargeback systems.

Now let us look at pricing models for compute, because choosing the right model is where the largest cost savings come from.

The default pricing model is pay-as-you-go. You are charged the full list price, billed per second, with no commitment. This is the most expensive option but the most flexible — appropriate for unpredictable or short-lived workloads.

Reserved Instances offer up to 72 percent discount compared to pay-as-you-go in exchange for a commitment to a specific virtual machine size and region for one or three years. You choose between three payment options: full upfront, monthly payments, or no upfront payment. The reserved capacity is applied automatically to any matching virtual machine running in your subscription. Instance size flexibility means one reservation can cover virtual machines of different sizes within the same instance series — for example, a D2s v5 reservation can also cover a D4s v5 at a proportional rate. Reserved Instances are also available for Azure S-Q-L Database, Cosmos D-B, App Service Premium plans, and A-K-S nodes. Reserved Instances are best for workloads that run 24 hours a day, 7 days a week, all year.

Savings Plans offer up to 65 percent discount in exchange for committing to a fixed hourly spend — for example ten dollars per hour — for one or three years. Savings Plans are more flexible than Reserved Instances because the commitment is not tied to a specific virtual machine size or region. The same Savings Plan covers virtual machines, App Service, Azure Functions Premium, A-K-S, and Azure Spring Apps. Savings Plans are better than Reserved Instances when your workloads frequently change size or move between regions.

Spot virtual machines use Azure's unused capacity at up to 90 percent discount compared to pay-as-you-go. The trade-off is eviction risk — Azure can reclaim a Spot V-M with only 30 seconds notice when the capacity is needed elsewhere. Spot V-Ms are appropriate for fault-tolerant, interruptible workloads such as batch data processing, C-I-C-D build agents, rendering jobs, and machine learning training runs. They are not appropriate for production web servers, databases, or any workload that cannot tolerate interruption.

Azure Hybrid Benefit lets you bring your existing Windows Server or S-Q-L Server licences — with active Software Assurance — to Azure, saving up to 85 percent on the licence component of Windows V-M costs. This is one of the highest-impact cost optimisations available to organisations already running Microsoft workloads on-premises. Azure Hybrid Benefit also applies to Azure S-Q-L Database, S-Q-L Managed Instance, and S-Q-L Server running on virtual machines.

Discounts stack. Combining a Reserved Instance with Azure Hybrid Benefit on a Windows V-M can reduce the cost to roughly 20 percent of the standard pay-as-you-go price. Development and test subscriptions available to Visual Studio subscribers receive further discounted rates on V-Ms and many services for non-production use.

Now let us look at cost optimisation strategies beyond pricing models.

Right-sizing means matching the virtual machine size to actual workload requirements. Azure Advisor analyses V-M utilisation metrics and identifies machines where C-P-U or memory utilisation is consistently below threshold. A virtual machine running at 3 percent average C-P-U is a candidate for a smaller S-K-U or shutdown. Right-sizing is often the first optimisation opportunity because many workloads are initially over-provisioned.

Auto-shutdown for development and test virtual machines is a simple and highly effective optimisation. A V-M that runs 12 hours per day instead of 24 costs exactly half as much. Azure DevTest Labs and the auto-shutdown feature on individual V-Ms make this easy to configure. For production workloads, auto-scaling with virtual machine scale sets and A-K-S node pools ensures you only pay for capacity when demand requires it. Azure S-Q-L serverless automatically pauses the database after a configurable idle period and resumes on the next connection — you pay for storage during the pause and only for compute when queries are running.

For storage, lifecycle management policies automatically move blob objects from the Hot tier to the Cool tier to the Cold tier to the Archive tier as they age. Archiving data you rarely access can reduce storage costs by 95 percent compared to Hot tier. You should also audit for unattached managed disks — when a virtual machine is deleted without deleting its disk, the disk continues to incur charges. Azure Advisor surfaces these orphaned disks.

For networking, keeping traffic within the same Azure region avoids cross-region egress charges. Using Private Endpoints routes traffic through the Azure backbone rather than the public internet, reducing both egress costs and latency. Azure Front Door and Azure C-D-N cache content at edge locations, reducing the volume of data that must be fetched from origin and therefore reducing egress charges.

Tagging is essential for cost visibility at scale. Tags are key-value pairs applied to resources — for example environment equals production, team equals platform, cost-centre equals CC-1234. In Cost Analysis you can group and filter spending by any tag. Azure Policy can enforce that all resources must have specific tags, making it impossible to deploy resources without the metadata needed for cost allocation.

Now let us look at Azure Advisor for cost recommendations.

Azure Advisor is the built-in recommendation engine across five pillars: Cost, Security, Reliability, Operational Excellence, and Performance. The Cost pillar surfaces actionable recommendations including: right-size or shut down underutilised V-Ms, purchase Reserved Instances for consistently running V-Ms, purchase Savings Plans based on your usage patterns, apply Azure Hybrid Benefit to eligible V-Ms, delete unprovisioned ExpressRoute circuits that are incurring charges without providing connectivity, and remove unattached static public I-P addresses. Each recommendation shows the estimated monthly saving. Implementing all active Cost recommendations brings your Advisor Cost Score to 100.

Finally, let us look at billing structures.

Enterprise Agreements are for large organisations committing to a minimum annual Azure spend. They offer Azure Prepayment — formerly called Monetary Commitment — where you pay upfront for Azure credits at a discount. EA customers get a negotiated price sheet, a department and account hierarchy for internal chargeback, and access to the E-A Portal for billing management.

The Microsoft Customer Agreement is the modern billing agreement replacing E-A for most customers. It has a simpler three-level structure: a billing account containing billing profiles, which contain invoice sections. Invoice sections map to departments or cost centres. Everything is managed through the Azure portal.

The Cloud Solution Provider programme lets you purchase Azure through a Microsoft partner. The partner handles billing and support and may bundle additional managed services. Costs may be higher than direct E-A pricing, but the partner adds service value.

For cost isolation, a common pattern is to separate production and non-production workloads into different subscriptions under a management group hierarchy. Non-production subscriptions can use Dev/Test pricing, different Azure Policy assignments, and lower budget limits. A dedicated sandbox subscription can have an enforced spending cap to prevent uncontrolled experimentation costs.

To summarise. Azure's default pay-as-you-go model is the most expensive — use Reserved Instances for 24/7 steady-state workloads, Savings Plans for flexible compute, and Spot V-Ms for fault-tolerant batch workloads. Apply Azure Hybrid Benefit if you have Windows Server or S-Q-L Server licences with Software Assurance. Use Cost Analysis to understand where your money is going. Set budgets with alerts so you are notified before overspending occurs. Act on Azure Advisor Cost recommendations to right-size V-Ms, purchase reservations, and remove orphaned resources. Enforce resource tagging with Azure Policy so every pound or dollar of spending can be attributed to a team, environment, or project. And use separate subscriptions for production and non-production to isolate costs and take advantage of Dev/Test pricing.

In the next topic, we will look at the Azure Well-Architected Framework — the five pillars of reliability, security, cost optimisation, operational excellence, and performance efficiency that guide the design of well-architected Azure solutions.
